				<span class="text-link">Online Virality, Broadcast Visibility, and the Incentives for Extreme Rhetoric</span> - Job Market Paper (New draft coming soon!)
				<!-- Abstract Section -->
				<p class="mt-2 ml-4 text-[0.75rem]">
					Does going viral on social media buy access to television? This paper studies whether viral success serves as a bridge from low barrier platforms to television, a high barrier gatekeeping arena. Using a dataset linking roughly 700,000 tweets by Italian Members of Parliament (MPs) from 2018 to 2022 to daily speaking time on major talk shows and newscasts, I estimate a dynamic difference in differences around days when an MP reaches the top 1 percent of engagement across all MP tweets. Viral MPs experience clear increases in next day television invitations, with effects concentrated on private channels, consistent with market driven gatekeeping. I then show that extreme rhetoric, defined as institutional delegitimization, group based discrimination, or zero sum framing, strongly predicts virality and increases the probability of reaching the threshold. A simple supply side model with a single MP rationalizes these incentives: producers use virality as a noisy signal of audience interest, citizens discount exaggeration but engage expressively, and the MP optimally exaggerates rhetoric to trade reputation for visibility.
				</p>
			</li>
